The '''USS ''Wayne E. Meyer'' (DDG-108)''' is an [[Arleigh Burke class destroyer|''Arleigh Burke''-class]] guided missile [[destroyer]] in the [[United States Navy]]. She is named after [[Rear Admiral]] [[Wayne E. Meyer]], who is known as the Father of [[Aegis combat system|Aegis]]. The ship is part of Destroyer Squadron Twenty-one (DESRON-21) of [[Carrier Strike Group Three]] which is currently headed by the Nimitz-class nuclear-powered aircraft carrier [[USS John C. Stennis (CVN-74)|USS ''John C. Stennis'' (CVN-74)]].

''Wayne E. Meyer'' is the 58th destroyer in her class. She carries the 100th [[Aegis combat system|AEGIS Weapon System]] to be delivered to the United States Navy.<ref>[http://www.courierpostonline.com/article/20091010/NEWS01/910100366 "Destroyer to be named for weapons developer"], ''[[Courier-Post]]'', 10 October 2009.</ref> She was built by [[Bath Iron Works]], and was christened by sponsor Anna Mae Meyer (wife of Admiral Meyer) and launched on 18 October 2008.

''Wayne E. Meyer'' completed sea trials in June 2009 and was delivered to the Navy in July 2009.<ref Name="NNS090710-15"/> She was Commissioned and placed into active service on the Delaware River in [[Philadelphia]], Pennsylvania on 10 October 2009. ''Wayne E. Meyer'' arrived at her homeport in San Diego, CA on 4 December 2009.<ref>[http://www.meyer.navy.mil/Site%20Pages/FAQ.aspx FAQ]</ref>

''Wayne E. Meyer'' celebrated her first Change of Command on 8 April 2011 with Executive Officer CDR Leo Albea relieving the ships first Commanding Officer CDR Nick Sarap. 

''Wayne E. Meyer'' made her maiden deployment as part of the John C. Stennis Strike Group from 29 July 2011 until 27 February 2012. She made port calls in Malaysia, Japan, South Korea, Thailand, Bahrain, Dubai, and the Philippines.

==Commanding Officers==
The commanding officer (CO) of the USS Wayne E. Meyer (DDG-108) is the United States Navy officer who is the most senior officer on ship. The CO is the ultimate authority over operations of the Wayne E. Meyer and her crew.

